We factor and rearrange the terms in the factorials:

\begin{align*}
\frac{3\cdot 5! + 15\cdot 4!}{6!} &= \frac{3\cdot 5! + 3\cdot 5!}{6!} \\
&= \frac{2\cdot 3 \cdot 5!}{6!} \\
&= \frac{6!}{6!} \\
&= \boxed{1}
\end{align*}

We begin by recognizing that since $27 = 3^3$, $7\sqrt{27}$ simplifies to $7\cdot3\sqrt{3}=21\sqrt{3}$. Our expression then becomes  \begin{align*}
\frac{8}{3\sqrt{3}+21\sqrt{3}} & = \frac{8}{24\sqrt{3}} \\
& = \frac{1}{3\sqrt{3}} \\
& = \boxed{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{9}}.
\end{align*}

